{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585916","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585916"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:21:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:21:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15033"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15033","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15033"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.32,0.16,0.16,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7721"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116266"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7721","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7721"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15033"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98262"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8115"},{"type":"tags","id":"8121"},{"type":"tags","id":"10538"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18858"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18862"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116266","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116266"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe anion gap is calculated by subtracting the sum of major measured anions from the major measured cation:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnion gap = [Sodium] - ([Chloride] + [Bicarbonate])\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EReference range: 8-16 mmol/L\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following conditions is most likely to cause a normal anion gap metabolic acidosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Diabetic ketoacidosis","Renal tubular acidosis","Chronic kidney disease","Salicylate poisoning","Lactic acidosis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn normal anion gap metabolic acidosis, the decrease in bicarbonate is matched by an increase in chloride, maintaining electroneutrality. \u003Cstrong\u003ERenal tubular acidosis\u003C/strong\u003E is a classic example, where the primary defect is either impaired bicarbonate reabsorption or inadequate acid secretion by the renal tubules.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other conditions listed cause elevated anion gap metabolic acidosis due to accumulation of unmeasured anions. \u003Cstrong\u003EDiabetic ketoacidosis\u003C/strong\u003E results from accumulation of ketone bodies (acetoacetate and beta-hydroxybutyrate). \u003Cstrong\u003EChronic kidney disease\u003C/strong\u003E leads to retention of phosphates, sulfates and other organic acids. \u003Cstrong\u003ESalicylate poisoning\u003C/strong\u003E causes accumulation of salicylic acid and ketone bodies. \u003Cstrong\u003ELactic acidosis\u003C/strong\u003E occurs due to accumulation of lactate. In these conditions, the unmeasured anions increase the gap between measured cations and anions above the reference range.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Normal anion gap metabolic acidosis occurs when bicarbonate is lost or chloride is retained, maintaining electroneutrality.","Renal tubular acidosis is characterized by normal anion gap metabolic acidosis due to impaired bicarbonate reabsorption or acid secretion.","Elevated anion gap metabolic acidosis occurs when unmeasured anions accumulate, such as ketones, lactate, or toxins."],"references":["Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). 